Linux (ELF) — entry & exit
✅ Entry point

In Linux assembly (no C runtime), you define:

global _start
_start:
_start is the real entry point used by the linker
No main unless you link with libc
✅ Exit (syscall)

You exit using a syscall:

mov rax, 60     ; syscall: exit
mov rdi, 0      ; exit code
syscall
🔹 Full minimal example
section .text
global _start

_start:
    mov rax, 60     ; exit syscall
    xor rdi, rdi    ; return 0
    syscall

✔ No function call
✔ Direct kernel interaction
----
Windows (PE) — entry & exit

Windows is more layered.

✅ Entry point options
Option A: With C runtime (common)
mainCRTStartup

or

main
Option B: No CRT (pure assembly)

You define your own entry like:

global start
start:

…but you must tell the linker:

/ENTRY:start
✅ Exit (Windows API)

Instead of syscall, you call:

ExitProcess

Example:

extern ExitProcess

section .text
global start

start:
    sub rsp, 32        ; shadow space
    mov rcx, 0         ; exit code
    call ExitProcess
